Make the fallback an explicit error branch so future registry changes surface immediately:

```ts
function lineToGroup(line: FoodLine): FoodGroup {
  if (line === "meat_fish" || line === "eggs_dairy" || line === "vegetable_protein") return "protein";
  if (line === "grains" || line === "vegetables" || line === "fruit") return "carbs";
  if (line === "oils" || line === "dairy_fats" || line === "nuts_seeds") return "fats";
  if (line === "sauces_condiments" || line === "herbs_spices") return "seasoning";
  // exhaustive check — TypeScript should never reach here
  const _exhaustive: never = line;
  throw new Error(`lineToGroup: unhandled FoodLine "${String(_exhaustive)}");
}
```

With the `never` assertion TypeScript will emit an error the moment a new FoodLine is added without being handled here.

Use the full state objects as dependencies:

```ts
}, [currentZoom, context, geometry]);
```

This is slightly broader but eliminates the fragility and is the idiomatic React pattern. The memoisation value is identical because the objects change by reference when state changes.

Either document explicitly that `geometry` must be a stable reference (e.g. a module-level constant), or add a `useEffect` that resets zoom to overview when geometry identity changes:

```ts
useEffect(() => {
  setCurrentZoom(geometry.zoomLevels.overview);
  setContext({});
}, [geometry]);
```

Wrap both derivations in `useMemo`:

```ts
const target = useMemo(
  () => deriveTarget(context, currentZoom.level),
  [context, currentZoom.level],
);
const transformStyle = useMemo(
  () => buildTransformStyle(currentZoom),
  [currentZoom],
);
```

This is a low-effort improvement that prevents spurious SVG repaints when unrelated state changes.

